summary: This document is a chain of emails from March 2020 between an FBI Special Agent and a 'LE Request' contact (likely a law enforcement liaison at a company, possibly Expedia) regarding a subpoena for records related to Ghislaine Maxwell. The company representative, Michelle, states they need more identifying information (like email addresses or credit card numbers) to search their databases and, after not receiving a response, closes the case.

events.title: Subpoena Received by Company
events.description: A subpoena related to Ghislaine Maxwell was received by the company (likely Expedia) from the FBI.

events.title: Company Requests More Information
events.description: Michelle from the company responds to the FBI subpoena, stating they need more identifying information (email addresses, credit card numbers, itinerary numbers) to search their databases for records related to Ghislaine Maxwell.

events.title: Case Closed Due to Lack of Response
events.description: Michelle informs the FBI Special Agent that, having not received the additional requested information past the 30-day mark, the company is closing the case.

keyFacts: The FBI was actively investigating Ghislaine Maxwell in early 2020, issuing a subpoena (dated January 27, 2020, per an attachment) to a company, likely Expedia, for records.
The company could not locate records using only a name and date of birth; they required specific identifiers like email addresses, credit card numbers, or itinerary numbers to search their databases.
The FBI agent provided at least one additional email address for the search on February 12, 2020, but the company found no records associated with it.
Due to the FBI not providing sufficient identifying information within 30 days, the company closed the investigative request on March 17, 2020.
The communication highlights a practical challenge in digital investigations: companies often need very specific digital footprints (emails, payment info) to retrieve records, not just names.
